### The tea industry in Sri Lanka

Sri Lanka is the [fourth largest
producer](https://lanka.com/about/interests/ceylon-tea/) of tea in the world
and also the second largest exporter. The country's central highlands and low-
elevation areas boast numerous tea estates which benefit from a climate that
produces high-quality tea. Over the years, tea from Sri Lanka or “Ceylon Tea”
has grown in popularity — almost one-fifth of the teas sold around the world
are from Sri Lanka.

The industry employs (directly or indirectly) [over 1 million
people](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tea_production_in_Sri_Lanka). Many of
the [500,000 tea estate workers](https://www.ucanews.com/news/activists-issue-
warning-to-tea-industry/41663) are Tamils descended from cheap laborers
[brought to Sri Lanka from India](https://spark.adobe.com/page/lhDga3kElCqda/)
by the British colonial rulers in the 19th century, and more than half of the
workers are women.

[![](https://globalvoices.org/wp-
content/uploads/2019/01/8358504543_285818eb38_k-800x450.jpg)](https://www.flickr.com/photos/nh53/8358504543/)

Sri Lankan tea plantation workers weighing plucked tea leaves which will
determine their daily wage. Image by Flickr user NH53. CC BY 2.0

### Severely Low Wages

Traditionally, workers have been paid [severely low
wages](https://www.bbc.com/news/business-17674937) compared to the national
average. In many cases, they have to collect 16kg to 18kg worth of tea per day
or their pay is halved. They are subjected to harsh [living and working
conditions](https://www.wsws.org/en/articles/2018/12/21/sril-d21.html), and
some of them sustain [painful
injuries](https://groundviews.org/2017/08/22/like-drought-parched-earth-the-
painful-injuries-sustained-by-tea-pluckers/) with little medical support from
the tea estates.

Approximately a decade ago, they were protesting to [increase the daily
wage](http://www.ipsnews.net/2009/09/sri-lanka-tea-workersrsquo-demand-for-
higher-wages-hits-a-snag/) to 500 rupees (US$4 in 2009) from 290 rupees
(US$2.5 in 2009). But their demands were not met as the industry [was hit by
the global recession](http://www.lankanewspapers.com/news/2009/3/41052.html)
and some tea estates were forced to lay off workers.

In 2016, their daily wage was increased by a mere Rs.50 to Rs. 500. Over the
years, the Sri Lankan Rupee has
[depreciated](https://groundviews.org/2018/09/22/money-talks-some-facts-
around-the-depreciation-of-the-sri-lankan-rupee/) while the cost of living has
increased. Their daily wage corresponds to US$2.75 in today's currency, so, in
essence, their wage has not increased in a decade.

As a result, the poverty level among plantation workers has increased,
although the overall poverty in Sri Lanka has declined in the past decades:

> (3/3) “Political leaders, if you can survive on Rs 625/day, then we don’t
> need Rs 1000/day”
>
> Protesters today challenged politicians to live on Rs. 625/day- the same
> wage proposed for
> [#plantation](https://twitter.com/hashtag/plantation?src=hash&ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw)
> workers in the collective bargaining agreement.
